legislators are having second thoughts 
about a unique law that grants confidentiality to pedophiles who 
confess to psychiatrists 
although the legislature removed some privileges last year 
maryland remains the only state that grants patientdoctor privilege 
if the pedophile discloses sexual abuse of children or even simple 
child abuse that occurred before seeking treatment from a 
psychiatrist who specializes in treating pedophilia 
dr fred berlin head of the johns hopkins sexual disorders 
clinic said in a recent interview that if he were required by law 
to report a pedophiles past that person probably wouldnt come 
forward for treatment 
he and others in his specialty won special confidentiality 
privileges from the general assembly in 1987 to encourage pedophiles 
to get help 
now the lawmakers want to force psychiatrists to report 
instances of past abuse that a pedophile reveals at any time even 
at his initial psychiatric evaluation 
child advocates and social services officials backing the bill 
maintain its more important to protect a childs rights than to 
guarantee any privacy to the offender 
stuart comstockgay the maryland american civil liberties 
unions executive director said the bill presents an interesting 
privacy issue 
the state aclu has yet to take a final position on the proposed 
change which passed the senate last month the house has yet to 
schedule debate on the bill 
theres always a balance between individual rights and another 
interest in the public safety and public health comstockgay said 
im sure on the surface it must seem its good for children to 
report the abuse and bad not to said berlin who believes more 
abuse may be uncovered by encouraging pedophiles to enter treatment 
noting that clergymen who counsel pedophiles and lawyers who 
refer them to psychiatrists for treatment are not compelled by law 
to report them he added my concern is that people who otherwise 
might have come forward would be deterred from doing so 
for example without the assurance of confidentiality one of his 
patients an attorney involved sexually with his daughter never 
would have sought help nor would therapists necessarily have gotten 
his daughter into counseling berlin said 
theres no way he wanted to risk being disbarred he very much 
wanted treatment berlin said 
