march 
hungarian politburo reformer imre pozsgay created conflict among 
communists two weeks ago with a stunning reevaluation of the 
antisoviet revolt of 1956 
pozsgay said the revolt was a popular uprising not a 
counterrevolution as his party had called it for 32 years 
his comments touched off intense public debate and led to the 
central committee meeting 
the committee statement and groszs remarks on television 
indicated there had been a compromise on reassessing the revolt 
grosz said that over the years the party had forgotten those 
popular elements that started the uprising against the stalinist 
regime of matyas rakosi on oct 23 1956 
but he said by the time the soviets had crushed the uprising on 
nov 4 1956 counterrevolutionary forces were leading the revolt 
western diplomats and some hungarians active in the dozens of 
alternative political groups started recently said they believed the 
outcome of the central committee meeting was a victory for pozsgay 
who has pushed hard for a multiparty system 
