<TEXT>
the soviet union said monday it is readying a 
series of laws in the human rights field including freedom of the 
press and the right to leave the country 
we are trying to implement fully our legislation in accordance 
with international standards said felix stanevski the soviet 
chief delegate to the un human rights commission 
we are well aware that only by guaranteeing human rights and 
freedoms can we open up the whole potential of our society he 
said in a speech in the 40nation commission 
only by such guarantees he said can the soviet union improve 
the standards of living and quality of life of the people solve the 
tasks of the environment and move science and technology forward 
he said measures already adopted over a short period of time 
shall improve the situation of the people in the soviet union in a 
broad range of areas 
among the measures he mentioned were new provisions ensuring 
the right of the mentally ill and the opening of new monasteries 
and churches 
soon there will be another series of laws he said these 
have to do with the areas of freedom of conscience of information 
and the press of social organizations and of entry and exit 
into and from the country 
reform of the soviet criminal code also is being prepared he 
said additional guarantees which will exclude the possibility of 
prosecution for political and religious convictions are also under 
way 
in a brief interview with the associated press stanevski said 
the soviet union probably would join a key human rights protocol 
that would allow its citizens to turn invidually to a un body if 
they feel wronged 
it would give the un human rights committee the right to 
examine the complaints and take the matter up with the soviet 
government 
only about one fourth of the un member nations have ratified 
that optional protocol to the international covenant on civil and 
political rights which is a binding instrument under 
international law most countries including the united states are 
reluctant to join the protocol which went into effect in 1976 
