the federal trade commission said monday that a 
pittsburgh company will donate 600000 to three medical 
associations to settle complaints of false advertising 
the ftc said general nutrition corp signed a consent decree 
under which it pledged not to make false or unsubstantiated claims 
about its products 
signing the decree is not an admission of any violations 
violation of its terms can mean a fine of 10000 
the commission said the company made false and unsubstantiated 
claims that its healthy greens diet supplement was effective in 
reducing the risk of cancer 
also the commission said the company falsely claimed that six 
other supplements mainly sold to body builders promoted weight 
loss increased muscle growth and slowed aging 
the consent order was approved by a 31 vote commissioner margot 
machol did not participate the dissenter commissioner mary l 
azcuenaga said the order left the company free to sell products 
it knows are deceptively labeled 
the money will be split among the american heart association the 
american diabetes association and the american cancer society 
c stephen baker a lawyer handling the case in the commissions 
chicago office said such required donations were rare but had been 
used in the past 
such a remedy was chosen he said because it would be 
extraordinarily difficult or impossible to identify the people who 
had bought this stuff and should get refunds 
