vandals are believed to have punctured six rubber 
seals that shut off water running from a st lucie nuclear plant 
reactor to the steam generator authorities said monday 
the plant near fort pierce on floridas southeastern coast was 
inactivated for refueling at the time and the damage was caught 
before the seals were installed said stacey shaw spokeswoman for 
florida power amp light co 
damage to the seals which are intended to stop water flow to the 
generator during inspections were discovered feb 7 during a 
preinstallation check 
there is basically little safety significance attached but the 
fact that they were apparently vandalized is significant said ken 
clark spokesman for the us nuclear regulatory commissions 
regional office in atlanta 
he said although the water going to the generator might be 
radioactive any leak caused by the punctures would have been 
spotted immediately even if they had somehow been installed in 
addition ms shaw said the rubber seal must be inflated before 
installation and the punctures made that impossible 
the vandalism apparently occurred during the three days before 
the inspection during that time the seals were on a loading ramp 
one day and in the containment building for the next two days ms 
shaw said 
weve interviewed a couple of dozen people that were in the 
area over the threeday period and so far they have not uncovered 
anything she said 
she said the utility has written a letter to plant personnel 
asking for help in the investigation but so far has identified no 
suspects 
it was possible the seals had been damaged by accident she said 
but emphasized the company was proceeding on the assumption it was 
vandalism 
if a suspect is identified he or she would be subject to federal 
criminal charges ms shaw said 
the fbi was informed of the incident but was not actively 
involved in the case she said 
clark said the nrc sent an inspector to the plant after the 
discovery but was now monitoring the utilitys internal 
investigation 
ms shaw said she did not expect the incident to hold up the 
restart of the 850megawatt unit 2 which was shut down for 
refueling at the end of january and should be back on line after 12 
weeks 
she also said the incident was not considered serious enough to 
cause a change in safety procedures at the plant 
