the robust economy 
there just arent enough people to go around said ian wade 
chairman of the 78member retail management association of the 
british colonys 57 million population 
hong kongs economy expanded 135 percent in 1987 and an 
estimated 8 percent last year sending the unemployment rate 
tumbling to a negligible 13 percent for the three months ending in 
november jimmy mcgregor who represents business interests in the 
local legislature estimates that at least 100000 more workers are 
needed 
business leaders say the shortage endangers future growth and 
forces up wages fueling inflation which neared 8 percent last 
year the government however says bringing in foreigners who do 
not have special skills would deprive local workers of their fair 
share of hong kongs economic success and could create numerous 
social problems 
the shortage is felt in virtually every industry from gritty 
construction sites to the plush corridors of the fivestar tourist 
hotels 
employers are taking a wide variety of measures to cope 
the hong kong and shanghai bank short nearly 300 tellers as the 
hectic lunar new year holiday approached in early february 
attempted to relieve the strain on its employees by giving away two 
porsche cars in a contest open only to customers who used automatic 
banking machines spokeswoman fionajane kennedy said 
the new marriott hotel angered competitors by instituting a 
48hour fiveday work week instead of the industry standard of six 
days 
kent maury the marriott marketing director said the fiveday 
week was designed to give his hotel a competitive edge in 
attracting staff its done exactly what we wanted he said 
adding that 3800 people applied for 1100 openings 
meanwhile hundreds of hong kong manufacturers have established 
plants across the border in chinas guangdong province where wages 
are relatively cheap land is available and labor is abundant 
the critical construction industry has been particularly hard hit 
by the scarcity of labor with the vast majority of projects failing 
to make completion deadlines according to gerrit j de nys chief 
executive of shui on contractors ltd 
the situation is exacerbated by laborers who are not working as 
hard aware of how valuable a commodity they have become de nys 
said 
if you yell and shout at them they wont even say goodbye 
theyll just walk off the job 
shui on now tends to focus more on public sector projects because 
the government seems less likely to demand penalty payments for the 
inevitable delays de nys said 
compounding the personnel headache faced by de nys and others is 
the loss of thousands of key professionals who are emigrating before 
china takes over the colony in 1997 
while there appears to be no quick fix to stem the emigration 
flow businessmen believe the labor shortage could be relieved if 
the government relaxed immigration restrictions that generally allow 
the entry of only specially skilled workers and maids 
nine major business associations have joined forces and are 
preparing a report on their labor needs in hopes of persuading the 
government to ease up on immigration 
mcgregor who is involved in the project said the government 
could tap china for labor to do shortterm contractual work 
englishspeaking workers needed in service industries could be 
brought in from the philippines malaysia and possibly thailand he 
said 
so far the government has refused to budge 
secretary for education and manpower ron bridge said in a 
november speech that importing workers who do not have special 
skills would be extremely damaging to our labor relations and 
reduce the incentive for employers to upgrade technology management 
and productivity 
further he said the supply of housing medical and social 
services and our transport facilities would be stretched even 
tighter and hong kong could face international accusations of 
exploiting cheap labor 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0167 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after years of delay the greek cypriot 
community is founding a university in an effort to halt an exodus of 
talented students and help reunify the wardivided mediterranean 
island 
but when the cyprus university opens next year it will be 
competing for international recognition with a 3yearold turkish 
cypriot university also seeking to become a prestigious higher 
education center 
although greek and turkish cypriot educators say they want 
students from both communities the islands longrunning political 
problems make that unlikely 
our university will teach in both greek and turkish and 
therell be a department of turkish studies the greek cypriot 
education minister andreas philippou said in an interview 
we want it to contribute to reuniting cyprus we hope turkish 
cypriots will attend but it depends on the political situation 
professor okan tarhan head of the east mediterranean university 
at famagusta in the turkish cypriot republic in northern cyprus 
said we have students from 17 countries but no greek cypriots 
cyprus was unofficially partitioned in 1974 when the turkish army 
invaded after an athensinspired coup intended to unite the island 
with greece 
the breakaway turkish cypriot statelet was proclaimed in 1983 in 
the northern onethird of the island occupied by the turkish forces 
reunification talks between greek and turkish cypriot leaders on 
a united nationproposed bizonal federation resumed last fall after 
a threeyear break but have bogged down amid traditional differences 
some greek cypriot officials fear that the de facto partition of 
the island will harden as time goes by with new generations growing 
up on both sides with no contact with each other 
cyprus is a tiny place but theres a great hunger for higher 
education said margit schatzman an american educational 
consultant preparing a study on the cyprus universities 
both the greek and turkish cypriot institutions are structuring 
their programs along mainstream western university lines its clear 
theyre both looking for international status she said in a 
telephone interview from milwaukee wis 
education minister philippou a former mathematics professor at 
patras university in greece said the university plan was drawn up 
in three months last summer by a group of politicians and cypriot 
academics including professors at us and british universities 
the decision to have a university was taken almost 20 years ago 
but never implemented he said now it must happen if were to 
stop losing good people who go abroad to study 
the greek cypriot university is due to open in 1990 in temporary 
premises with 400 students and 30 faculty and eventually grow to 
4000 students and 330 faculty members it is budgeted to cost 42 
million 
the planners say that having a local university will save a large 
chunk of an estimated 24 million spent every year on sending 10000 
cypriots to greek british and american universities 
many start careers overseas because with more than 50000 
graduates among the 480000 greek cypriots jobs at home are hard to 
find at home 
the government offers free business courses to recent graduates 
to make them employable in cyprus booming service economy but 
with our own university we can channel people where theyre needed 
by offering developmentrelated courses philippou said 
young greek cypriots say they welcome a university because it 
will make nicosia livelier as well as saving family funds 
the university will bring lots of activities therell be more 
music and cultural activities im looking forward to it said 
eleanor palaiologou who wants to study management 
the greek cypriot parliament will decide whether some courses 
should be taught in english but with a business school planned 
that may be essential to attract firstrate staff and students 
several educators said 
the east mediterranean university where courses are taught in 
english has a problem because it is in the turkish cypriot 
republic which is recognized only by turkey 
were an international university but we dont qualify for aid 
from any international organization said tarhan the universitys 
head 
i think thats unfair since were an educational institution 
and not involved in politics 
foreigners from arab countries iran and pakistan make up around 
10 percent of its 2300 students the rest are turks and turkish 
cypriots but they also may spend a year taking intensive english 
classes before starting as freshmen 
east mediterranean a former junior technical college upgraded to 
a university in 1986 focuses on engineering and economics tarhan 
said a business school will open and more humanities courses will be 
offered in the next two years 
</TEXT>
