editors note chicagoans go to the polls this week in a special 
mayoral election to decide who will serve the last two years of the 
second term of the late harold washington the citys first black 
mayor the leading candidates are two blacks hoping to win over 
washingtons supporters and the son of the longtime political boss 
richard j daley 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the ghosts of two former mayors are hovering over 
the campaign trail as voters in the nations thirdlargest city 
decide who will lead them into the 1990s 
long gone is the late mayor richard j daley a boss of the old 
school who used concentrated political muscle to run chicago for 21 
years before his death in 1976 
but the frontrunner in the special democratic mayoral primary is 
one of his sons richard m daley the 46yearold cook county 
states attorney whose blood ties to city hall legend sometimes seem 
to transcend his own record 
gone as well is harold washington the citys first black mayor 
whose death on nov 25 1987 set the stage for this years special 
election 
but his legacy of leadership is a key issue for black voters 
being wooed by mayor eugene sawyer 54 daleys chief primary rival 
and alderman timothy evans 45 who is running a thirdparty 
campaign on the harold washington ticket 
at stake in the special mayoral contest are the last two years of 
washingtons second term 
in the democratic primary sawyer and daley also face lawrence 
bloom a white alderman who supported washington and two lagging 
candidates three republicans none well known in this democratic 
stronghold were on the gop ballot 
after the feb 28 primary elections evans will take on the 
winners in the april 4 general election 
this campaign season in a city known for its deep racial 
divisions black voters who united behind washington are being 
ardently courted by sawyer and evans 
neither can supplant the affable streetwise washington who has 
become a symbol of change and unity for many chicagoans 
harold washingtonembodied all of the hopes and aspirations 
of a generation of people who genuinely believed that chicago was 
ready for reform said cook county recorder of deeds carol moseley 
braun who last fall became the first black to win a major county 
office 
five weeks before the primary sawyer elected by the city 
council to succeed washington finally won the endorsement of civil 
rights leader and presidential contender jesse jackson 
he has done more than any of his primary opponents to sustain 
the harold washington coalition jackson said 
but the delay in that longawaited endorsement underscores the 
discord in the black community since washingtons death 
and jackson declined to say where he would stand if sawyer faced 
evans in the general election 
evans who served as washingtons floor leader in the city 
council is campaigning as the late mayors heir apparent his 
withdrawal from the democratic primary prevented a split in the 
black vote that would have virtually guaranteed daley the nomination 
jacksons endorsement was a matter of great concern to both black 
candidates but some observers say it wont help sawyer 
a massive black turnout is sawyers only chance in the primary 
said paul kleppner author of chicago divided the making of a 
black mayor and director of the social science research institute 
at northern illinois university in de kalb 
my suspicion is that he sawyer is going to get the 
overwhelming bulk of the black vote with moderate turnout and 
that wont be enough he said 
sawyer still has the image that he was put in there by the 
white aldermen kleppner said referring to the role of longtime 
washington foes in engineering sawyers election over evans as 
acting mayor in december 1987 
time heals a lot of wounds counters joseph gardner 
washingtons former political office director who endorsed sawyer 
and predicts a strong black turnout for him 
the racial breakdown of chicagos votingage population on july 1 
was about 468 percent white 383 percent black and 149 percent 
hispanic said marie bousfield chicagos city demographer 
</TEXT>
