the stars we are capitol marc almond 
 
when was the last time you heard lyrics like these 
ill be a dragonfly a butterfly a secret or a little lie to 
test you a song a verse a lullaby a symphony 
in my hands the grains of sand a thousand million moments of 
emotion oh these my dreams are yours 
im a teardrop in a storm a storm at the end of the world 
set words like these to a rock beat and add strings trumpets and 
other lush instrumentation backing vocals with plenty of 
atmospheric reverb and an occasional spokenword passage what do 
you have donovan the moody blues king crimson 
no this is not a lost 1967 recording of early art rock but marc 
almond and his group la magia exhibit a youthful romanticism that 
has been missing from rock since the flower power days 
thats refreshing as a break from the current formulas a 
revitalization of an almost extinct style and its reassuring to 
know that even in the late 80s a songwriter can refer to himself as 
someone who is afraid of getting jaded 
but youthful romanticism and idealism can lead to youthful 
excess and this record is often both trite and overwrought in its 
efforts to achieve poetry in a song called the very last pearl 
almond aptly sings call me romantic call me deluded he 
concludes another song by drawing out the phrase and i a fool 
for love really now 
amid such excess however there are some good songs on this 
album only the moment and tears run rings in particular 
stand out as wellrealized pop songs that manage to escape being 
overdone all it takes is a little restraint 
by dan murphy associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
wall of pride columbia omar and the howlers 
 
omar and the howlers play the kind of loud rowdy rock n roll 
that sounds best late at night in a noisy crowded bar 
that doesnt mean you have to invite a bunch of strangers over to 
your apartment and throw beer bottles against the wall to enjoy 
wall of pride the texas bands second album but make no 
mistake its party music all the way 
transferring such barband energy to a record is no easy task but 
producer terry manning who has worked with bluesrockers zz top 
and george thorogood has a way with this sort of thing 
the focus is not on the songs which are good if not overly 
distinctive as much as the sound itself especially the sandpaper 
growl of lead singer omar who also plays a raw scraping guitar 
hes helped by a strong rhythm section and keyboard player eric 
scortia who apparently isnt afraid to occasionally use his elbows 
instead of his fingers to pound the piano 
the albums two cover songs are interesting a remake of the 
animals we gotta get out of this place which abandons any 
pretense to the subtlety of the original and a version of jimmy 
reeds down in mississippi recorded in an odd muffled sound 
that recalls the great bluesmans loping style 
the originals most of which are written or cowritten by an 
otherwise unidentified k dykes range from the allout boogie of 
rattlesnake shake to the rhythm and bluesflavored kings 
ransom 
thats not a very far range but these guys dont claim to be 
renaissance men theyre howlers 
by marc rice associated press writer 
