<TEXT>
nasa scientists have created an animated 
threedimensional movie of mars seen from the view of an astronaut 
flying at 160000 mph through the planets canyons and above its 
volcanoes 
mars the movie lasts about two minutes and its simulated 
flight ranges from three miles to 500 miles above the surface of the 
red planet 
the film takes the viewer on a tour through valles marineris a 
canyon system near the martian equator that stretches farther than 
the distance from los angeles to new york and over tharsis montes 
a series of giant volcanoes more than twice the size of mount 
everest the space agency said 
the movie was made by imageprocessing scientists at jet 
propulsion laboratory which runs americas unmanned space 
exploration program for the national aeronautics and space 
administration 
it uses computerenhanced images taken by the viking orbiter 
spacecraft and was designed to give scientists a more complete view 
of earths neighbor and to demonstrate improvements in the labs 
ability to render 3d images 
production required 37 days of uninterrupted computer time or 15 
minutes for each of the films more than 3500 frames 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a drug used to combat high blood pressure 
shows promise as an alternative to surgery for treating prostate 
enlargement that afflicts up to 4 million american men a scientist 
says 
the prostate gland surrounds the neck of the bladder and the 
urethra in men and manufactures part of the fluid in semen 
for unknown reasons it gradually enlarges after age 35 most men 
develop symptoms if they live long enough said dr perinchery 
narayan chief of urology at the san francisco veterans 
administration medical center 
two million to 4 million men suffer prostate enlargement to the 
point that the gland squeezes the urethra to impede urine flow from 
the bladder narayan said symptoms range from frequent urination 
and burning sensations to infections urine retention and 
lifethreatening kidney failure 
a preliminary study of 22 men found that four weeks of treatment 
with the drug terazosin provided 30 percent to 50 percent 
improvement in urine flow he said it looks like theres enough 
relief that our patients can avoid surgery whether this is 
permanent remains to be seen 
terazosin is used to treat high blood pressure because it relaxes 
smooth muscle in blood vessels researchers believe it has the same 
effect on smooth muscle in the urinary tract opening the urethra 
despite the enlarged prostate the drug doesnt appear to reduce the 
size of the enlarged gland 
the va and university of california san francisco plan to try 
terazosin on more 50 to 75yearold men with enlarged prostates 
other scientists in the nationwide study are at washington 
university medical center in st louis the university of 
wisconsinmadison hospital tulane university medical center in new 
orleans and the university of california san diego medical 
center 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
dairy cows are getting prepaid medical 
care under a university of illinois program modeled on health 
maintenance organizations 
in the past veterinarians have been thought of as people who 
provide individual animal medicine or emergency care said howard 
whitmore head of food animal medicine and surgery at the 
universitys college of veterinary medicine but this is a new 
program to broaden the use and role of the veterinarian in the 
animal industry 
for a fixed monthly fee based on herd size the college provides 
all medical services including hospitalization when needed and 
routine biweekly visits university spokesman larry bernard called 
wellcow care 
the program helps owners keep medical costs under control allows 
the veterinarians to influence cattle management and use a variety 
of skills and also provides veterinary students with valuable 
experience 
we study them as they grow and monitor them all the way through 
so we raise these animals efficiently grow them at the right rate 
breed them at the right time calve them at the right time and 
manage for maximum milk production and profit whitmore said 
the veterinarian wants to be viewed as a herd health consultant 
not just a person who delivers emergency care 
