<TEXT>
japans trade surplus rose in january over a year 
ago as low oil prices continued to keep down import costs the 
finance ministry reported monday 
the surplus grew to 325 billion last month from 307 billion 
in january 1988 but was well below the monthly record of 965 
billion set in december 
january exports rose 115 percent from a year earlier to 1932 
billion and imports climbed 127 percent to 1607 billion the 
figures are compiled as the goods pass through customs 
japans surplus with the united states however fell slightly 
over a year ago to 2974 billion from 2976 billion exports to 
the us market increased 111 percent to 650 billion while 
imports from the united states surged 224 percent to 352 billion 
finance ministry officials said japans overall surplus rose 
because of steady demand for japanese goods in other countries 
enjoying continued economic expansion and because of lower prices 
for the crude oil japan imports 
they said imports of manufactured goods remain strong a trend 
they expect to continue for some time 
in trade with the united states japan boosted car exports by 97 
percent to 150 billion in january us steel sales in japan 
soared sixfold to 4119 million and car sales nearly doubled to 
4162 million 
japans exports to the european economic community rose 64 
percent to 366 billion in january while imports from the eec 
leaped 244 percent to 202 billion that left japan with a surplus 
of 164 billion down from 182 billion in january 1988 
because of large oil imports japan ran a 104 billion deficit 
in trade with the middle east down from 130 billion in january 
1988 
