involved in minor skirmishes with people who stayed on the job 
its report was brief and did not say whether anyone was injured 
it was believed to be the first such action by factory authorities 
in communist yugoslavia 
sources said on condition of anonymity that no one was seriously 
injured they said security men literally pushed the strikers out 
of the factory gates 
tanjug said mill authorities responded to the improper and 
rowdy behavior of some strikers which endangered the security of the 
people and the installations at the mill 
the agency said the situation in the plant 90 miles southwest of 
belgrade became volatile when management announced monday 
afternoon that it would not give in to the strikers demands tanjug 
said 
belgrade television said the factory produced 400 tons of steel 
less on monday than in a usual day it also showed some of the 
skirmishes between strikers and workers 
about 22000 people work at the mill which was built after world 
war ii and served as a symbol of communist industrial development 
until it began losing money in recent years 
nearly 2000 strikes were reported in yugoslavia last year most 
of them to protest lower living standards brought about by the 
nations severe economic problems 
</TEXT>
