<TEXT>
market figures for january indicate 
semiconductor demand is increasing for the first time in four months 
and that the contracting market may be slightly reversing itself 
analysts said monday 
an increase in us semiconductor orders caused a rise in the 
closely watched booktobill ratio for january which reached 
10 according to figures released by the semiconductor industry 
association the figure was 93 in december 
a booktobill ratio of 10 means that for every 100 worth of 
products billed manufacturers received 100 worth of new orders or 
bookings 
the total shipments or billings of 1004 million in january 
were 109 percent higher than the same figure a year ago and 171 
percent lower than in december 
the january 1989 orders or bookings of 1124 million were 58 
percent higher than the average bookings posted last year and 54 
percent higher than decembers figure 
it means the industry is coming back toward a growth 
environment after four months with less than a onetoone ratio 
indicating a shrinking of the market and people buying less from 
september to now said mel phelps of the hambrecht amp quist 
investment company 
this indicates for the first time they are beginning to order 
as much as is being produced he said 
</TEXT>
