<TEXT>
a west german team has found two 
coal deposits containing about 93 million tons of coal worth an 
estimated 256 billion it was reported tuesday 
the two deposits were found in the tebulan and merit south areas 
of sarawak state the new straits times reported quoting sp chen 
sarawaks geological survey department director the coal is of the 
subbituminous type suitable for industrial use as fuel 
the new areas are adjacent to the existing merit pila coal field 
180 miles northeast of kuching which was discovered last april and 
has about 637 million tons of coal worth more than 172 billion 
chen said 
chen said the discovery was part of a 11 milliondollar survey 
being conducted by seven west german geologists since 1983 the 
seven are in sarawak as part of a german technical aid program that 
ends in 1990 
chen said there were about 78 million tons of coal in the tebulan 
area and 15 million tons in merit south 
commercial mining at the merit pila coal field began last june by 
the united statesbased global mineral exploration corp and a 
malaysiansouth korean joint venture lucky hill ltd chen said 
global was expected to produce 350000 tons annually and lucky 
hill 120000 tons so far global has produced 29500 tons and lucky 
hill 20500 tons the coal is being exported to taiwan and japan 
</TEXT>
